.\"
.SH "NEWSGROUP SELECTION COMMANDS"
.TP 10
.B 4
Select group 4.
.TP
.B ^R
Reset \fI$HOME/.newsrc\fP file. This will destroy all records of which
articles have been read, so use this carefully.
.TP
.B #
Choose a range of articles to be affected by the next command. See the section
RANGES for more information.
.TP
.B /
Search for a group by name and description (if displayed).
.TP
.B ?
Backward search through the group names and descriptions.
.TP
.B <CR>
Read current group.
.TP
.B <TAB>
Enter next group with unread news. Will wrap around to the beginning of the
group selection list looking for unread groups.
.TP
.B c
Make current group as all read [after confirmation] and move to the next
group in the group selection list.
.TP
.B C
Mark current group as all read [after confirmation] and enter the next
unread group in the group selection list.
.TP
.B d
Toggle display to show just the group name or the group name and the group
descriptions.
.TP
.B g
Choose a new group by name. This command can be used to access any group, even
those not currently yanked in.
.TP
.B h
Help screen of newsgroup selection commands. You can use \fB/\fR and
\fB?\fR to search on this screen.
.TP
.B H
Toggle the display of help mini menu at the bottom of the screen.
.TP
.B i
Toggle the display of the description of the current newsgroup in the last line.
This will not be available if \fBtin\fR was started with the \fB-d\fR option.
.TP
.B I
Toggle inverse video.
.TP
.B m
Move the current group within the group selection list.
By entering `1' the group will become the first displayed group in
the list, by entering `8' the eighth group in the list etc. By
entering `$' the group will be the last group displayed.
.TP
.B M
User configurable options menu (for more information see section
GLOBAL OPTIONS MENU AND TINRC CONFIGURABLE VARIABLES).
.TP
.B n
Enter next group with unread news. This key is identical to \fB<TAB>\fR
.TP
.B N
Positions the cursor on the next group with unread articles in it.
.TP
.B q
Quit \fBtin\fR - ask the user to confirm if 'confirm_to_quit' is on.
.TP
.B Q
Quit \fBtin\fR - don't ask the user to confirm.
.TP
.B r
Toggle display of all subscribed to groups and just those groups containing
unread articles. Command has no effect if groups were specified on the command
line when \fBtin\fR was started.
.TP
.B R
Mail a bug report or comment to <tin-bugs@tin.org>. This is the best way of
getting bugs fixed and features added/changed.
.TP
.B s
Subscribe to current group.
.TP
.B S
Subscribe to groups matching user specified pattern.
.TP
.B u
Unsubscribe to current group. This can be used to remove bogus groups.
See 'strip_bogus' in the GLOBAL OPTIONS MENU AND TINRC CONFIGURABLE VARIABLES
section.
.TP
.B U
Unsubscribe to groups matching user specified pattern.
.TP
.B w
Post an article to current group. If posting fails for some reason, you'll
get the chance to edit (`e') the article again, postpone (`o') it for later
processing (see also ``\fB-o\fR''command-line switch) or discard (`q') it.
.TP
.B X
Quit \fBtin\fR without saving any changes to the configuration.
.TP
.B y
Yanks in all groups.
Toggles the displayed groups between all the groups in the
\fI$NEWSLIBDIR/active\fP file and just those that are subscribed to in
\fI$HOME/.newsrc\fP.
.TP
.B Y
Reread the active file to see if any new news has arrived since
starting \fBtin\fR.
.TP
.B z
Mark all articles in the current group as unread.
.TP
.B Z
Identical to \fBz\fR.
.\"--------------------------------------------------------------------
.\"
.SH "GROUP INDEX COMMANDS"
.TP 10
.B 4
Select article 4.
.TP
.B ^A
Auto select article(s) using a menu. Read the section FILTERING ARTICLES
for more information.
.TP
.B ^K
Kill article(s) using a menu. Read the section FILTERING ARTICLES for
more information.
.TP
.B #
Choose a range of articles to be affected by the next command. See the section
RANGES for more information.
.TP
.B -
Re-enter the last message that was viewed.
.TP
.B /
Search forward for specified subject.
.TP
.B ?
Search backward for specified subject.
.TP
.B *
Select current thread for later processing.
.TP
.B +
Perform auto-selection on current group.
.TP
.B \\.
Toggle selection of current thread. If at least one unread article,
(but not every unread article) in the current thread is selected, then all
unread articles become selected.
.TP
.B ;
For each thread in current group, if it at least one unread
article is selected, all unread articles become selected. This is
useful for auto-selection on author where reader wants to
see entire thread.
.TP
.B =
Prompts for a pattern with which to match on. All threads
whose subjects match the pattern will be marked selected. A pattern
of ``*'' will match all subjects. Entering just <CR> will re-use the
last pattern that was entered.
.TP
.B @
Reverse all selections on all articles.
.TP
.B ~
Undo all selections on all articles. It clears the toggle effect
of `X' command. Thus after first doing a `X', one can then do `~'
to reset articles. Thus, one can iteratively whittle down
uninteresting threads.
.TP
.B |
Pipe current article / thread / auto-selected (hot) articles /
articles matching pattern / tagged articles into command.
See the section MAILING PIPING PRINTING REPOSTING AND SAVING ARTICLES for
more information.
.TP
.B [
Auto select article(s) with a single key [after confirmation]. The defaults
used for selection are based upon the following four tinrc config variables:
.in +.3i
.nf
default_filter_select_case
default_filter_select_expire
default_filter_select_global
default_filter_select_header
.fi
.in -.3i
Read the section GLOBAL OPTIONS MENU AND TINRC CONFIGURABLE VARIABLES for
a full explanation of these variables and FILTERING ARTICLES for more
information on filtering.
.TP
.B ]
Kill article(s) with a single key [after confirmation]. The defaults used
for killing are based upon the following four tinrc config variables:
.in +.3i
.nf
default_filter_kill_case
default_filter_kill_expire
default_filter_kill_global
default_filter_kill_header
.fi
.in -.3i
Read the section GLOBAL OPTIONS MENU AND TINRC CONFIGURABLE VARIABLES for
a full explanation of these variables and FILTERING ARTICLES for more
information on filtering.
.TP
.B <CR>
Read current article.
.TP
.B <TAB>
View next unread article or group.
.TP
.B a
Author forward search.
This searches for articles with a specific From: line.
.TP
.B A
Author backward search.
Otherwise, see 'a' above.
.TP
.B B
Search the body of all articles in group (can be slow).
You can abort the search using 'q'.
.TP
.B c
Mark all articles as read [after confirmation] then return to the
group selection list.
.TP
.B C
Mark all articles as read [after confirmation] and enter the next group
with unread news.
.TP
.B d
Cycle the display of the author through all the possible options
for the tinrc variable 'show_author'.
.TP
